snippet.textDisplay:
I actually kinda liked Cats. It wasn't horrible, but the cast was amazing, I liked the music.
I didn't like how extremely cursed it was. The fur covering human hands and feet, that one scene where Taylor Swift got everybody high, also the Mice and Cockroaches, it was like watching a 2-hour long cursed image. I liked the music alright but at points found myself squirming uncomfortably, or squirming out of boredom.
On the other hand, I think Idris Elba did a really good job, I loved every one of those scenes he was in. I thought the train scene was fun, and throughout most of this the choreography was amazing, which is to be expected because the guy who directed this choreography also directed the choreography for Hamilton.

Overall, I give it a 5/10. It wasn't great but it was okay, and interesting enough that I'd sit through it again.

snippet.textDisplay:
Few things

1. It took me until 2:36 to realize that you were using a green screen for the background

2. The person who decided that this was a great musical for a live action movie was a complete and utter idiot. The majority of the theater community hates cats and would only see it for the costumes, which were fantastic for the broadway and tour productions. With this you don’t get the costumes so it’s incredibly hard to enjoy.

3. The plot in very unclear. ALW got the idea for the musical from some weird poetry book and one of them didn’t quite “fit” and was pretty confusing to understand. This is why it doesn’t make sense. The composer legit didn’t know wth was going on.

4. ALW came out with two musicals that year so one of them was bound to suck, in this case it was cats.

ALW- Andrew Lloyd Webber (big broadway composer, wrote Cats along with many broadway classics)

Feel free to correct me if anything’s incorrect

snippet.textDisplay: as a person that was in the stage version of cats (as Grizabella), can say wholeheartedly that this should not have been made into a film. with the amount of love I have for this piece of art, it didn't work at all as a movie. it should have never been made, cats is a ballet. kind of like an interpretive piece of art. you have to interpret what you are seeing on stage in a way that will make sense to you personally because of all the different things happening on stage(being the "odd" dancing and the way the cats move around the stage to tell a story). you can see what you want to see and take away what you want. yet with this being made into a movie the director makes you see what you have to see to make the story make sense. not leaving anything up to the imagination and just kinda telling you "hey, this is what's happening, so you better like it". so with all that being said.  burn it burn it please kill it with fire.

snippet.textDisplay: Tbh a lot of it being unintelligible and unsatisfying isn't the movies fault. That's just it being true to the source material, it's a buzzard musical with basically no plot. The only time the songs actually make sense is when you read them as poetry, the way T.S.Elliot wrote them. Cos then you're not looking for some kind of a plot or overarching theme or characters you give a shit about. You're just reading a bunch of cute, unrelated poems about cats.

snippet.textDisplay: My friend and I went to see it to make fun of it. It was so bad that we could not. The entire theater was packed and not a single other person there was there to watch the Cats movie. We had the whole room to ourselves and still couldn’t bring ourselves to even make fun of the movie. We just sat there, disturbed and confused. Every song in the movie lasted about 5 minutes longer than necessary. We kept waiting for the final song to end but lion cat kept looking into directly into the camera and saying that cats are not dogs. Also what was up with Thanos cat? The only redeeming quality of the movie was Jason Derulo screaming MIIIILK
